SIMPLE: perdition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Perdition
<hw>Per*di"tion</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧r*d⟦icr⟧sh"⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>perditio</ets>, fr. <ets>perdere</ets>,
<ets>perditum</ets>, to ruin, to lose; <ets>per</ets> (cf. Skr.
<ets>par⟦amac⟧</ets> away) + <ets>-dere</ets> (only in comp.) to put;
akin to Gr. <grk>tiqe`nai</grk>, E. <ets>do</ets>. See
<er>Do</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Entire loss; utter destruction;
ruin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mere <qex>perdition</qex> of the Turkish fleet.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(religion)</fld> <def>Damnation; the utter loss of
the soul, or of final happiness in a future state; future misery or
eternal death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If we reject the truth, we seal our own <qex>perdition</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>J. M. Mason.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Loss or diminution.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hell; hades; <as>as, on the path to
<ex>perdition</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perditionable</ent>⟦br⟧
